const respiratory: Question[] = [
  q('resp001','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 65-year-old man with a 40-pack-year smoking history presents with worsening dyspnoea and a FEV₁/FVC ratio of 0.62 and FEV₁ 48% predicted. He has 2 exacerbations per year. He is currently on a SABA only. What is the most appropriate step-up treatment?',
    ['Add inhaled corticosteroid (ICS) alone','Add a LAMA (tiotropium)','Add LABA + ICS combination','Start oral prednisolone','Add a LABA alone'],
    1,
    'In COPD with FEV₁ 30–49% (GOLD stage 3) and ≥2 exacerbations per year, NICE NG115 recommends adding a long-acting muscarinic antagonist (LAMA, e.g. tiotropium) to SABA. ICS is added (as LABA+ICS or triple therapy LAMA+LABA+ICS) for those with blood eosinophils ≥300 cells/μL or frequent exacerbations despite dual bronchodilators. LAMA reduces exacerbation frequency more effectively than LABA in COPD.',
    'COPD + ≥2 exacerbations: add LAMA (NICE NG115)'),

  q('resp002','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 70-year-old woman with known COPD presents with acute exacerbation. She is confused, RR 28, O₂ sat 82% on air, HR 118, BP 100/60. ABG on 28% O₂: pH 7.22, pCO₂ 8.9 kPa, pO₂ 7.1 kPa, HCO₃ 28. What is the most appropriate next step?',
    ['Increase O₂ to 60%','Non-invasive ventilation (NIV) with BIPAP','Immediate intubation and mechanical ventilation','Oral prednisolone and salbutamol nebs','IV aminophylline infusion'],
    1,
    'This patient has type 2 respiratory failure with respiratory acidosis (pH 7.22, pCO₂ 8.9 kPa) despite supplemental oxygen, indicating COPD exacerbation with ventilatory failure. NIV (BiPAP) is the first-line intervention (NICE NG115) — it reduces mortality, intubation rate, and hospital stay. Target O₂ sats are 88–92% in COPD. Intubation is reserved for NIV failure or contraindications. High-flow O₂ risks hypercapnia.',
    'COPD + type 2 failure + acidosis = NIV (BiPAP) first-line'),

  q('resp003','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 35-year-old woman with asthma presents with wheeze, cough, and dyspnoea. PEFR is 55% of best. She has taken 10 puffs of salbutamol in 4 hours with minimal improvement. What severity is this and what treatment is required?',
    ['Mild asthma — continue salbutamol and review in 24 hours','Moderate asthma — add oral prednisolone','Acute severe asthma — admit, nebulised salbutamol + ipratropium, IV hydrocortisone, O₂','Life-threatening asthma — immediate intubation','Brittle asthma — IV magnesium sulphate only'],
    2,
    'PEFR 33–50% best = acute severe asthma. Management: high-flow O₂, back-to-back nebulised salbutamol 2.5–5 mg, ipratropium bromide 0.5 mg nebulised, IV/oral prednisolone 40–50 mg (or IV hydrocortisone 100 mg). Life-threatening features: PEFR <33%, silent chest, cyanosis, bradycardia, exhaustion. Consider IV magnesium 1.2–2 g for refractory cases. Admit all acute severe attacks.',
    'PEFR 33-50% = acute severe asthma → nebulisers + steroids + O₂'),

  q('resp004','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 55-year-old non-smoker presents with progressive dyspnoea and dry cough. HRCT shows bilateral basal ground-glass opacities and honeycombing. Spirometry shows a restrictive pattern with reduced TLCO. Bronchoalveolar lavage shows 15% neutrophils. What is the most likely diagnosis?',
    ['Hypersensitivity pneumonitis','Sarcoidosis','Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF)','Cryptogenic organising pneumonia','Desquamative interstitial pneumonia'],
    2,
    'IPF presents in older adults (>60) with progressive exertional dyspnoea and dry cough, restrictive spirometry, reduced TLCO, and HRCT showing basal/subpleural honeycombing with or without ground-glass opacification — typical UIP pattern. BAL neutrophilia (not lymphocytosis) is seen. Honeycombing distinguishes UIP/IPF from NSIP (no honeycombing). Anti-fibrotic therapy (nintedanib or pirfenidone) slows progression.',
    'IPF: age >60 + basal honeycombing + restrictive + ↓TLCO'),

  q('resp005','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 40-year-old woman presents with bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy on chest X-ray, erythema nodosum, and arthralgia. She is otherwise well. What is the most likely diagnosis and what is the next investigation?',
    ['Lymphoma — CT-guided biopsy','Sarcoidosis (Löfgren syndrome) — serum ACE and CT chest','Tuberculosis — sputum cultures','Metastatic cancer — PET scan','Hypersensitivity pneumonitis — avian precipitins'],
    1,
    'Löfgren syndrome is an acute form of sarcoidosis with the classic triad: bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy, erythema nodosum, and acute arthritis/arthralgia. It carries an excellent prognosis and often self-resolves. Serum ACE is elevated in 60–80% of sarcoidosis cases. CT chest characterises lymph node and pulmonary involvement. BAL showing CD4:CD8 >3.5 supports the diagnosis. Histology (non-caseating granuloma) confirms if needed.',
    "Löfgren's = BHL + erythema nodosum + arthritis = sarcoidosis"),

  q('resp006','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 50-year-old pigeon fancier presents with dry cough, dyspnoea, and constitutional symptoms over 6 months. HRCT shows bilateral ground-glass opacities and centrilobular nodules. Spirometry is restrictive with low TLCO. Avian precipitins are positive. What is the treatment?',
    ['Oral prednisolone and antigen avoidance','Mycophenolate and azathioprine','Nintedanib (anti-fibrotic)','Pirfenidone','LABA + ICS combination'],
    0,
    'Chronic hypersensitivity pneumonitis (extrinsic allergic alveolitis) is caused by repeated inhalation of organic antigens (pigeon protein here). Avian precipitins confirm sensitisation. Treatment combines antigen avoidance (most important — rehoming birds) and systemic corticosteroids (prednisolone 40 mg tapering). Immunosuppressants (azathioprine, mycophenolate) are added for refractory or steroid-sparing. Anti-fibrotics are not first-line. Without avoidance, disease progresses.',
    'Hypersensitivity pneumonitis: antigen avoidance + prednisolone'),

  q('resp007','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 30-year-old woman presents with right-sided pleuritic chest pain and haemoptysis. O₂ sats 94%, HR 110, BP 120/80. ECG shows sinus tachycardia. Wells score pre-test probability is 5 (moderate). D-dimer is 1.8 mg/L. What is the next step?',
    ['Start LMWH empirically and discharge','CT pulmonary angiography (CTPA)','Ventilation-perfusion (V/Q) scan','Reassure and discharge','Lower limb Doppler ultrasound'],
    1,
    'NICE NG158 recommends CTPA as first-line imaging for suspected PE (Wells ≥5 or intermediate/high probability). D-dimer is used only in low probability scores (Wells <5) — if positive in low probability, CTPA is then indicated. In this case, Wells 5 = moderate/high probability, so CTPA directly. V/Q scan is an alternative when CTPA is contraindicated (e.g. allergy, renal failure, pregnancy). Empirical anticoagulation is started while awaiting CTPA if delay expected.',
    'Moderate/high Wells PE probability → CTPA (NICE NG158)'),

  q('resp008','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 60-year-old man with COPD is found to have a resting O₂ saturation of 86% on two separate occasions. He has cor pulmonale and polycythaemia. What intervention has been shown to improve survival?',
    ['Long-term oxygen therapy (LTOT) ≥15 h/day','Pulmonary rehabilitation only','Theophylline','Oral prednisolone long-term','Roflumilast (PDE4 inhibitor)'],
    0,
    'LTOT (≥15 h/day) is the only medical therapy proven to improve survival in hypoxaemic COPD (PaO₂ ≤7.3 kPa or SaO₂ ≤88% at rest, or PaO₂ 7.3–8 kPa with cor pulmonale or polycythaemia). The MRC and NOTT trials demonstrated mortality benefit. Criteria per NICE NG115: sats ≤88% on ≥2 occasions at rest. Ambulatory O₂ is prescribed separately for exercise desaturation.',
    'Hypoxaemic COPD (sats ≤88%): LTOT ≥15h/day for survival benefit'),

  q('resp009','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 55-year-old man presents with central cyanosis, clubbing, and severe dyspnoea. SpO₂ 78%. CXR shows a left lower zone pulmonary arteriovenous malformation (PAVM). What is the underlying condition and treatment?',
    ['Primary PAH — sildenafil','Hereditary haemorrhagic telangiectasia (HHT) — embolisation of PAVM','Eisenmenger syndrome — bosentan','Lung cancer — surgery','Alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency — augmentation therapy'],
    1,
    'PAVMs are most commonly associated with hereditary haemorrhagic telangiectasia (Osler-Weber-Rendu disease — autosomal dominant, ENG/ACVRL1 mutations). Other features: epistaxis, telangiectasia on lips/fingers, GI bleeds, hepatic AVMs. Treatment: transcatheter embolisation of PAVMs (to prevent paradoxical embolism/stroke and hypoxaemia). All first-degree relatives should be screened.',
    'PAVM + telangiectasia + epistaxis = HHT → embolisation'),

  q('resp010','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 62-year-old woman is found to have a 1.5 cm solid pulmonary nodule on CT, new compared to imaging 2 years ago. She is a non-smoker with no risk factors. What is the recommended management?',
    ['PET-CT scan immediately','Serial CT at 3 months to assess growth','CT-guided biopsy','Surgical resection without further workup','Reassure — all small nodules are benign'],
    1,
    'NICE NG12 and BTS nodule guidelines: a new solid nodule 8–15 mm requires further assessment. Growth on interval CT is a key indicator of malignancy. A 3-month CT to assess volume doubling time is appropriate before PET-CT (which is recommended for nodules ≥8 mm with intermediate–high risk or persistent growth). PET-CT and/or biopsy follows growth confirmation. Brock and Herder models estimate malignancy risk.',
    'New solid nodule 8-15mm: 3-month CT to assess growth (BTS)'),

  q('resp011','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 45-year-old man presents with fever, productive cough, and right lower lobe consolidation on CXR. CURB-65 score is 1 (urea 5.2). He is sat 96% on air. What is the appropriate management?',
    ['Admit for IV antibiotics','Oral amoxicillin 500 mg three times daily and manage at home','IV co-amoxiclav and clarithromycin','Transfer to ITU','Await sputum cultures before starting antibiotics'],
    1,
    'CURB-65 0–1 = low severity community-acquired pneumonia (CAP): 30-day mortality <3%. NICE NG138 recommends outpatient management with oral antibiotics — amoxicillin 500 mg TDS for 5 days is first-line. CURB-65 ≥3 = severe CAP requiring IV antibiotics and admission. Penicillin allergy: clarithromycin or doxycycline. Sputum cultures are not required before starting antibiotics in low-severity CAP.',
    'CURB-65 0-1: outpatient amoxicillin (NICE NG138)'),

  q('resp012','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 70-year-old woman has CURB-65 score of 3 (confusion, urea 11, RR 32, BP 80/50, age 70). She has bilateral pneumonia. What is the antibiotic regimen?',
    ['Oral amoxicillin 1 g twice daily','IV co-amoxiclav 1.2 g + clarithromycin 500 mg BD','Oral doxycycline 200 mg loading then 100 mg daily','IV ceftriaxone 2 g daily alone','Oral levofloxacin 500 mg daily'],
    1,
    'CURB-65 ≥3 = severe CAP requiring hospital admission and parenteral antibiotics. NICE NG138 recommends IV beta-lactam (co-amoxiclav or benzylpenicillin) + IV macrolide (clarithromycin) for severe CAP to cover both typical and atypical organisms. Duration: 5–7 days IV, switch to oral when improving. Blood cultures and urine pneumococcal/Legionella antigen tests should be sent.',
    'Severe CAP (CURB-65 ≥3): IV co-amoxiclav + clarithromycin'),

  q('resp013','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 28-year-old woman presents with exertional dyspnoea, syncope, and a right parasternal heave. Echo shows RV pressure of 80 mmHg, dilated RV, and no left heart disease. Exclude CTEPH with V/Q scan (normal). What is the diagnosis and first-line treatment for PAH?',
    ['CTEPH — surgical endarterectomy','Idiopathic PAH — start sildenafil (PDE5 inhibitor) or ambrisentan (ERA)','Left heart disease — diuretics','Pulmonary veno-occlusive disease — warfarin','OSA — CPAP'],
    1,
    'Idiopathic PAH (IPAH) is characterised by elevated PVR, RV hypertrophy, and absence of secondary causes. V/Q excludes CTEPH. RHC confirms (mPAP ≥25, PAWP ≤15, PVR >3 WU). First-line treatment for intermediate-risk IPAH: combination oral therapy with PDE5 inhibitor (sildenafil, tadalafil) + ERA (ambrisentan, macitentan). IV prostacyclins for high-risk patients. Anticoagulation is not routinely recommended in IPAH (unlike CTEPH).',
    'IPAH: oral PDE5i + ERA combination first-line'),

  q('resp014','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 25-year-old man presents with a 2-day history of fever, productive cough, and pleuritic chest pain after returning from Southeast Asia. Sputum AFB smear is positive. He lives in a hostel. What is the most important immediate action?',
    ['Start standard 4-drug TB treatment (RHEZ)','Isolate the patient in a negative-pressure room immediately','Chest X-ray and await specialist review','Contact tracing only','Prescribe isoniazid prophylaxis to contacts'],
    1,
    'Smear-positive pulmonary tuberculosis is highly infectious. Immediate respiratory isolation in a negative-pressure single room is mandatory while investigations are confirmed and treatment is initiated. NICE CG117 recommends notification to Public Health England, contact tracing, and standard 6-month treatment (2 months RHEZ + 4 months RH). Drug sensitivity testing guides therapy.',
    'Smear-positive TB: immediate negative-pressure isolation'),

  q('resp015','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 35-year-old HIV-positive man (CD4 180 cells/μL) presents with fever, dry cough, and progressive dyspnoea. CXR shows bilateral interstitial shadowing. LDH is elevated. O₂ sats drop significantly on exertion. What is the most likely diagnosis and treatment?',
    ['Bacterial pneumonia — amoxicillin','Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia (PCP) — high-dose co-trimoxazole','Cryptosporidiosis — nitazoxanide','Mycobacterium avium complex — azithromycin','CMV pneumonitis — ganciclovir'],
    1,
    'PCP (Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia) is the most common AIDS-defining illness in patients with CD4 <200. Classic presentation: insidious onset dyspnoea, dry cough, fever, bilateral interstitial CXR infiltrates, elevated LDH, and exertional desaturation. Treatment: high-dose co-trimoxazole (trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole) for 21 days. Add prednisolone if PaO₂ <9.3 kPa. Primary prophylaxis with co-trimoxazole when CD4 <200.',
    'AIDS + CD4 <200 + bilateral infiltrates + exertional desaturation = PCP'),

  q('resp016','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 45-year-old woman with SLE on long-term hydroxychloroquine presents with new dyspnoea and CXR showing bilateral pleural effusions. She has no fever. ANA positive, anti-dsDNA 640. Pleural fluid is exudative (LDH ratio 0.7, protein ratio 0.65). What is the most likely cause?',
    ['Malignant pleural effusion','Lupus pleuritis','Parapneumonic effusion','Cardiac failure (transudative)','Mesothelioma'],
    1,
    'SLE is the most common connective tissue disease causing exudative pleural effusions (lupus pleuritis). It occurs in 30–50% of SLE patients. Active disease markers (elevated anti-dsDNA, low complement) support lupus activity as the cause. Treatment with NSAIDs, hydroxychloroquine, or corticosteroids depending on severity. Rule out infection and malignancy before attributing to SLE.',
    'SLE + exudative pleural effusion + active serology = lupus pleuritis'),

  q('resp017','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 68-year-old man with a 35-pack-year smoking history presents with haemoptysis, weight loss, and a right hilar mass on CXR. Bronchoscopy biopsy shows small cell lung cancer. CT staging shows mediastinal and liver metastases. What is the standard treatment?',
    ['Surgery (right pneumonectomy)','Platinum-based chemotherapy ± immunotherapy','Radical radiotherapy to chest','Palliative care only','VATS lobectomy'],
    1,
    'Small cell lung cancer (SCLC) is almost always extensive stage (>60% at diagnosis) and surgery is not appropriate. First-line treatment is platinum-based combination chemotherapy (etoposide + carboplatin/cisplatin). The addition of atezolizumab (PD-L1 inhibitor) has recently improved survival in extensive-stage SCLC (IMpower133 trial). Prophylactic cranial irradiation reduces CNS metastases in limited-stage disease. SCLC is highly chemosensitive initially.',
    'Extensive SCLC: platinum chemotherapy ± immunotherapy'),

  q('resp018','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 62-year-old woman with adenocarcinoma of the lung is found to have EGFR exon 19 deletion on molecular testing. She has stage IV disease (liver and bone metastases). What is the most appropriate first-line treatment?',
    ['Platinum-based chemotherapy (carboplatin + pemetrexed)','Osimertinib (third-generation EGFR tyrosine kinase inhibitor)','Pembrolizumab (PD-1 inhibitor)','Erlotinib (first-generation EGFR TKI)','Bevacizumab + carboplatin'],
    1,
    'EGFR-mutant NSCLC (exon 19 deletion or exon 21 L858R) responds dramatically to EGFR tyrosine kinase inhibitors (TKIs). Osimertinib (third-generation) is now the preferred first-line agent (FLAURA trial) as it also covers T790M resistance mutation, penetrates CNS, and has superior PFS and OS over first/second-generation TKIs. Pembrolizumab is used for PD-L1 ≥50% wild-type NSCLC. Chemotherapy is reserved for TKI failure.',
    'EGFR-mutant NSCLC → osimertinib first-line (FLAURA)'),

  q('resp019','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 55-year-old woman with newly diagnosed asthma fails to respond to salbutamol and low-dose ICS. She has nasal polyps and takes ibuprofen regularly for back pain. After taking ibuprofen, she develops severe bronchospasm. What syndrome does she have?',
    ['Allergic asthma triggered by NSAIDs','Samter\'s triad (aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease)','Beta-blocker-induced bronchospasm','Churg-Strauss syndrome (eosinophilic granulomatosis)','Aspirin-induced anaphylaxis'],
    1,
    'Samter\'s triad (aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease, AERD) comprises: asthma + nasal polyps + NSAID/aspirin hypersensitivity. It is not IgE-mediated. NSAIDs block COX-1, shunting arachidonic acid to leukotriene pathway, causing massive mast cell degranulation and bronchoconstriction. Treatment: strict NSAID avoidance, leukotriene receptor antagonists (montelukast), high-dose ICS, aspirin desensitisation in selected patients.',
    "Samter's triad: asthma + nasal polyps + NSAID hypersensitivity"),

  q('resp020','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 72-year-old man presents with a left-sided pleural effusion. Thoracocentesis reveals: straw-coloured fluid, pH 7.12, glucose 1.2 mmol/L, LDH 890 U/L, protein 48 g/L. He has had pneumonia for 10 days. What is the next step?',
    ['IV antibiotics alone and review in 48 hours','Chest drain insertion (pH <7.2 = complicated effusion)','Diagnostic CT chest only','Repeat aspiration in 1 week','Pleurodesis'],
    1,
    'Complicated parapneumonic effusions (pH <7.2, glucose <2.2 mmol/L, LDH >1000, positive Gram stain/culture) require chest drain insertion + IV antibiotics. pH <7.2 is the most important predictor of need for drainage. Simple parapneumonic effusions (pH >7.2, no loculation) can be managed with antibiotics alone. Empyema (frank pus) also requires drainage ± VATS decortication for loculated collections.',
    'Parapneumonic effusion pH <7.2 = chest drain insertion'),

  q('resp021','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 55-year-old man presents with worsening dyspnoea over 6 months. HRCT shows a mosaic attenuation pattern, air trapping on expiration, and centrilobular nodules bilaterally. He keeps budgerigars at home. What is the most likely diagnosis?',
    ['IPF','Subacute hypersensitivity pneumonitis','COPD','Sarcoidosis','Lymphangioleiomyomatosis'],
    1,
    'Subacute hypersensitivity pneumonitis shows HRCT features of mosaic attenuation (indicating small airways disease/air trapping), ground-glass opacities, and centrilobular nodules (reflecting granulomatous inflammation around terminal bronchioles). Budgerigar exposure is a common cause (avian proteins). Positive avian precipitins support the diagnosis. BAL shows lymphocytosis (CD8+ predominant). Treatment: antigen avoidance + corticosteroids.',
    'Budgerigar exposure + mosaic HRCT + centrilobular nodules = HP'),

  q('resp022','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 25-year-old man presents with sudden onset left-sided chest pain and dyspnoea after lifting weights. He is tall and thin. CXR shows a 3.5 cm left-sided pneumothorax with no mediastinal shift. He is haemodynamically stable. What is the most appropriate management?',
    ['Admit and observe for 4 hours then repeat CXR','Immediate needle decompression','Chest drain insertion','Aspiration with 16G cannula','Surgical pleurodesis'],
    3,
    'BTS guidelines: primary spontaneous pneumothorax (PSP) without significant symptoms: if rim >2 cm, aspiration is first-line treatment (16F/16G cannula at 2nd ICS MCL or 4th ICS midaxillary). If <2 cm and mild symptoms, discharge with safety-net advice. Intercostal chest drain is for failed aspiration, bilateral, or significant symptoms. Tension pneumothorax (mediastinal shift, haemodynamic compromise) = immediate needle decompression.',
    'PSP >2 cm: aspiration (BTS guidelines)'),

  q('resp023','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 58-year-old man presents with persistent cough for 4 months with haemoptysis. He is a smoker. CXR shows hilar lymphadenopathy. Bronchoscopy biopsy shows squamous cell carcinoma. CT shows no distant metastases. PET shows mediastinal N2 lymph nodes positive. What is the stage and treatment?',
    ['Stage I — surgery (lobectomy)','Stage IIIA — concurrent chemoradiotherapy','Stage IV — palliative chemotherapy','Stage II — surgery + adjuvant chemotherapy','Stage IIIB — radical radiotherapy alone'],
    1,
    'N2 mediastinal node involvement without distant metastases = stage IIIA NSCLC. For unresectable stage IIIA/IIIB, the standard of care is concurrent platinum-based chemoradiotherapy (cisplatin + etoposide or carboplatin + paclitaxel). After completing concurrent chemoRT, durvalumab (PD-L1 inhibitor) as consolidation therapy for 12 months has shown survival benefit (PACIFIC trial).',
    'Stage IIIA NSCLC: concurrent chemoRT + durvalumab consolidation'),

  q('resp024','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 40-year-old woman with systemic sclerosis (diffuse, anti-Scl-70 positive) develops progressive dyspnoea. HRCT shows bilateral basal ground-glass opacification and fine reticulation. Spirometry: FVC 68%, TLCO 55%. What is the most likely interstitial pattern and first-line treatment?',
    ['UIP pattern — pirfenidone','NSIP pattern — mycophenolate mofetil or cyclophosphamide','DIP pattern — stop smoking','LIP pattern — azathioprine','Organising pneumonia — prednisolone'],
    1,
    'Systemic sclerosis-associated ILD most commonly shows NSIP (non-specific interstitial pneumonia) pattern on HRCT — bilateral basal GGO and fine reticulation without honeycombing. Treatment: immunosuppression with mycophenolate mofetil (MMF, preferred over cyclophosphamide — SLS II trial) or nintedanib (anti-fibrotic, SENSCIS trial). Pirfenidone is approved for IPF (UIP pattern), not SSc-ILD primarily.',
    'SSc-ILD: NSIP pattern → mycophenolate mofetil'),

  q('resp025','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 20-year-old woman presents with episodic wheezing, breathlessness, and cough worse at night. Peak flow diary shows >20% variability. Spirometry shows FEV₁/FVC 0.68 with 15% improvement after salbutamol. What is the diagnosis and step 1 management?',
    ['COPD — LAMA','Asthma — regular low-dose ICS (beclometasone 200 mcg/day)','Bronchiectasis — airway clearance','Vocal cord dysfunction — speech therapy','Asthma — SABA alone is sufficient for mild asthma'],
    1,
    'Asthma: symptoms + airflow variability (PEFR variability >10–15%) + bronchodilator reversibility (≥12% and 200 mL improvement in FEV₁). NICE NG80: step 1 for newly diagnosed mild persistent asthma is low-dose ICS (e.g. beclometasone 200 mcg/day or equivalent) as regular preventer therapy, NOT SABA alone. SABA alone is no longer recommended as regular monotherapy (promotes airway inflammation).',
    'New asthma diagnosis: start ICS (not SABA monotherapy) — NICE NG80'),

  q('resp026','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 45-year-old woman is referred with resistant hypertension and obesity. She reports waking at night choking, morning headaches, and daytime somnolence. Epworth sleepiness score is 16. What is the diagnostic test?',
    ['Overnight pulse oximetry alone','Sleep study (polysomnography or home oximetry + actimetry)','Spirometry','CT chest','Thyroid function tests'],
    1,
    'Obstructive sleep apnoea is diagnosed with a sleep study. NICE recommends diagnostic sleep study (full polysomnography in complex cases; home-based oximetry/respiratory polygraph in typical presentations). An apnoea-hypopnoea index (AHI) ≥5/hour with symptoms confirms OSA. CPAP is first-line treatment for moderate-severe OSA (AHI ≥15). It improves daytime somnolence, blood pressure, and cardiovascular risk.',
    'OSA diagnosis: sleep study (AHI ≥15 = CPAP therapy)'),

  q('resp027','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 62-year-old woman presents with progressive dyspnoea and clubbing. Spirometry shows FVC 72%, FEV₁/FVC 0.82. HRCT shows subpleural, basal honeycombing and traction bronchiectasis with no ground-glass opacities. BAL: 5% lymphocytes, 8% neutrophils. Anti-MDA5 antibodies are negative. What are the treatment options?',
    ['Prednisolone alone','Azathioprine + prednisolone + N-acetylcysteine','Pirfenidone or nintedanib','Mycophenolate mofetil','Surgical lung biopsy to confirm before any treatment'],
    2,
    'Typical UIP pattern on HRCT (subpleural basal honeycombing ± traction bronchiectasis) with clinical context consistent with IPF does not require surgical biopsy for diagnosis (NICE 2017, ATS guidelines). Anti-fibrotic therapy: pirfenidone (ASCEND trial) or nintedanib (INPULSIS trial) slow FVC decline and reduce acute exacerbations. Immunosuppressants (prednisolone + azathioprine + NAC) were shown to cause harm in IPF (PANTHER trial).',
    'IPF (UIP): pirfenidone or nintedanib; avoid steroids/azathioprine (PANTHER)'),

  q('resp028','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 70-year-old man with severe COPD (FEV₁ 30%) is assessed for lung volume reduction surgery. What spirometric and emphysema distribution criteria favour benefit from this procedure?',
    ['Diffuse emphysema, FEV₁ <20%','Upper lobe predominant emphysema, FEV₁ >20%, low exercise capacity','Lower lobe emphysema, FEV₁ 50%','Bronchiectasis pattern, FEV₁ >50%','Any pattern with FEV₁ <30%'],
    1,
    'Lung volume reduction surgery (LVRS) or bronchoscopic lung volume reduction (endobronchial valves) benefit patients with: upper lobe predominant emphysema (the heterogeneous distribution allows the healthier lower lobes to expand), FEV₁ 20–45% predicted, and low exercise capacity (6MWT < median). The NETT trial showed mortality benefit specifically in upper-lobe predominant, low exercise capacity. Diffuse emphysema or FEV₁ <20% have worse outcomes with surgery.',
    'LVRS benefit: upper-lobe emphysema + FEV₁ 20-45% + low exercise capacity'),

  q('resp029','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 50-year-old man with COPD is found to have blood eosinophils of 350 cells/μL despite LAMA + LABA therapy. He has 3 exacerbations per year. What add-on therapy reduces exacerbations?',
    ['Oral prednisolone 5 mg long-term','Add ICS to form triple therapy (LAMA + LABA + ICS)','Add roflumilast (PDE4 inhibitor)','Add long-term azithromycin','Add montelukast'],
    1,
    'NICE NG115 recommends adding ICS to LAMA + LABA (triple therapy) for COPD patients with blood eosinophils ≥300 cells/μL and ≥2 exacerbations. In patients with eosinophils 100–299 and frequent exacerbations, ICS may also be considered. IMPACT trial showed triple therapy reduced exacerbations by 25% vs dual bronchodilation. Roflumilast is an option for chronic bronchitis phenotype (FEV₁ <50%, chronic productive cough). Azithromycin is added for non-smoking frequent exacerbators.',
    'COPD eosinophils ≥300 + ≥2 exacerbations: add ICS (triple therapy)'),

  q('resp030','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 38-year-old woman presents with dyspnoea and haemoptysis. CXR and CT show bilateral lung cysts (thin-walled, uniform, randomly distributed). She is a non-smoker. Serum VEGF-D is elevated. What is the most likely diagnosis?',
    ['LAM (lymphangioleiomyomatosis)','Birt-Hogg-Dubé syndrome','PLCH (pulmonary Langerhans cell histiocytosis)','Emphysema','Lymphoid interstitial pneumonia (LIP)'],
    0,
    'LAM is a rare cystic lung disease almost exclusively in pre-menopausal women. HRCT shows bilateral diffuse thin-walled cysts. Elevated serum VEGF-D (>800 pg/mL) is diagnostic without biopsy. TSC2 mutation (in tuberous sclerosis-associated LAM) or sporadic. Treatment: sirolimus (mTOR inhibitor) — MILES trial showed slowed FVC decline. Pneumothorax is a frequent complication. Transplant for end-stage disease.',
    'Bilateral cysts + woman + elevated VEGF-D = LAM → sirolimus'),

  q('resp031','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 32-year-old smoker presents with persistent cough and recurrent chest infections. CT shows cylindrical bronchial dilatation in both lower lobes with bronchial wall thickening. Sputum grows Pseudomonas aeruginosa. What is the most likely diagnosis?',
    ['COPD','Asthma','Bronchiectasis','IPF','Alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency'],
    2,
    'Bronchiectasis: abnormal, permanent bronchial dilation on CT (signet ring sign — bronchus wider than adjacent artery, bronchial wall thickening). Causes: post-infectious, cystic fibrosis, immunodeficiency, allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis. Pseudomonas colonisation is common and associated with worse prognosis. Management: airway clearance (active cycle of breathing), physiotherapy, inhaled hypertonic saline, prolonged macrolide antibiotics for frequent exacerbators, and treatment of underlying cause.',
    'Bronchial dilatation on CT + recurrent infections = bronchiectasis'),

  q('resp032','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 45-year-old man with cystic fibrosis (F508del homozygous) is deteriorating despite standard therapy. FEV₁ 58%. What CFTR modulator combination is most appropriate?',
    ['Ivacaftor alone (potentiator)','Elexacaftor + tezacaftor + ivacaftor (Kaftrio)','Lumacaftor + ivacaftor','Tezacaftor + ivacaftor only','No CFTR modulators available for F508del'],
    1,
    'Kaftrio (elexacaftor + tezacaftor + ivacaftor) is highly effective for patients with at least one F508del mutation (includes F508del homozygous). Triple combination corrects CFTR protein folding (elexacaftor + tezacaftor as correctors) and improves channel gating (ivacaftor as potentiator). NICE approved. Trial data show dramatic FEV₁ improvement, reduction in exacerbations, and improved quality of life. Ivacaftor alone is for G551D (gating mutations).',
    'CF F508del: Kaftrio (elexacaftor + tezacaftor + ivacaftor)'),

  q('resp033','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 65-year-old woman with NSCLC adenocarcinoma (PDL1 90%, EGFR/ALK/ROS1 wild-type) has stage IV disease. She is PS0. What is the most appropriate first-line treatment?',
    ['Carboplatin + pemetrexed','Pembrolizumab monotherapy','Nivolumab','Osimertinib','Carboplatin + paclitaxel + bevacizumab'],
    1,
    'For PD-L1 ≥50% with no targetable mutation (EGFR, ALK, ROS1), pembrolizumab monotherapy is first-line (KEYNOTE-024 trial: superior PFS and OS vs chemotherapy). For PD-L1 1–49%, pembrolizumab + chemotherapy is preferred. For actionable mutations (EGFR, ALK, ROS1, KRAS G12C, MET, BRAF, RET, NTRK), targeted therapy is preferred regardless of PD-L1 score. All stage IV NSCLC must have molecular testing before starting systemic therapy.',
    'PD-L1 ≥50% + no driver mutation: pembrolizumab monotherapy'),

  q('resp034','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 55-year-old man with suspected COPD has spirometry: FEV₁ 2.1 L (68% predicted), FVC 3.2 L (82% predicted), FEV₁/FVC 0.65. After salbutamol: FEV₁ 2.4 L (14% increase, 300 mL increase). What does this suggest?',
    ['Asthma — significant bronchodilator reversibility','COPD — partially reversible airflow obstruction','Normal spirometry','Restrictive lung disease','Upper airways obstruction'],
    1,
    'A post-bronchodilator FEV₁/FVC <0.7 confirms airflow obstruction consistent with COPD. Significant bronchodilator reversibility (≥12% AND ≥200 mL improvement in FEV₁) is present here (14%, 300 mL). However, NICE and GOLD define COPD primarily by the clinical picture and post-BD ratio <0.7, regardless of reversibility. Significant reversibility in COPD does not rule out or change the diagnosis, though it raises the possibility of an asthma-COPD overlap (ACO).',
    'Post-BD FEV₁/FVC <0.7 = COPD (reversibility doesn\'t exclude it)'),

  q('resp035','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 60-year-old man with a history of mesothelioma exposure (worked in shipbuilding) presents with right-sided pleuritic chest pain and a massive unilateral effusion. CT shows pleural thickening and nodularity. What investigation confirms the diagnosis?',
    ['Pleural fluid cytology alone','VATS pleural biopsy (video-assisted thoracoscopy)','CT-guided pleural biopsy','Sputum cytology','Bronchoscopy'],
    1,
    'Malignant pleural mesothelioma: pleural biopsy is required for diagnosis. VATS (video-assisted thoracoscopy) has the highest diagnostic yield (>90%) and allows direct visualisation of the pleura for biopsy from multiple sites. CT-guided biopsy is an alternative for localised disease or when VATS is contraindicated. Cytology alone is insufficient for mesothelioma. Immunohistochemistry (calretinin+, WT-1+, CK5/6+, CEA-, TTF-1-) confirms mesothelial origin.',
    'Mesothelioma: VATS pleural biopsy (highest yield)'),

  q('resp036','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 42-year-old woman of African descent presents with erythema nodosum, bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy, and a serum ACE of 78 U/L. She has asymptomatic hypercalcaemia (2.82 mmol/L). Urinary calcium is elevated. What explains the hypercalcaemia?',
    ['Primary hyperparathyroidism','Granulomatous conversion of 25-OH vitamin D to 1,25-OH vitamin D (calcitriol) by macrophages in granulomas','Bony metastases','PTHrP secretion by lymphoma cells','Immobilisation'],
    1,
    'Sarcoidosis causes hypercalcaemia through 1α-hydroxylase activity in macrophages within granulomas, which converts 25-OH vitamin D to 1,25-OH vitamin D (calcitriol) — the active form. This increases GI calcium absorption and bone resorption. PTH is suppressed. Elevated 1,25-OH vitamin D and low PTH are the hallmarks. Treatment: hydration, avoid sun/vitamin D, systemic corticosteroids (reduce macrophage activity).',
    'Sarcoidosis hypercalcaemia: macrophage 1α-hydroxylase → ↑calcitriol'),

  q('resp037','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 22-year-old man presents with sudden onset right-sided chest pain and breathlessness. He is tall and thin with long fingers. CXR shows a 25% right pneumothorax (rim >2 cm). He had a previous left-sided pneumothorax 1 year ago. What is the recommended management?',
    ['Observe with repeat CXR in 4 hours','Aspiration','Intercostal chest drain','Surgical pleurodesis referral','Discharge with safety-net advice'],
    3,
    'This man has had bilateral spontaneous pneumothorax — right now (25%), left previously. After a second ipsilateral or first contralateral pneumothorax, surgical pleurodesis (VATS with pleurectomy and/or pleurodesis) is recommended to prevent recurrence. Marfanoid features and bilateral PSP raise suspicion for Marfan syndrome or connective tissue disorder. Referral to thoracic surgery for pleurodesis is the next step after managing this episode.',
    'Second pneumothorax (contralateral/bilateral) = surgical pleurodesis referral'),

  q('resp038','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 60-year-old man is evaluated for a 6 cm cavitating right upper lobe lesion on CXR. He has night sweats, 8 kg weight loss, and haemoptysis. Sputum culture grows Aspergillus fumigatus. Serum Aspergillus IgG (precipitins) are markedly positive. What is the diagnosis and treatment?',
    ['Invasive pulmonary aspergillosis — IV voriconazole','Chronic pulmonary aspergillosis (CPA) — oral itraconazole or voriconazole for ≥6 months','Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis — prednisolone + itraconazole','Aspergilloma in a cavity — surgical removal','Tuberculosis reactivation — RHEZ'],
    1,
    'Chronic pulmonary aspergillosis (CPA) presents with chronic respiratory symptoms, weight loss, cavitating/nodular lesions, markedly elevated Aspergillus IgG (precipitins), and positive culture — often in patients with pre-existing lung disease (COPD, prior TB, structural disease). Treatment: long-term oral azole antifungals (itraconazole or voriconazole) for at least 6 months. Monitor for azole resistance. Simple aspergilloma in a cavity without symptoms may be observed.',
    'CPA: cavitating lesion + Aspergillus precipitins → long-term azole'),

  q('resp039','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 65-year-old woman presents with progressive dyspnoea and diffuse crackles. She is on amiodarone 200 mg daily for AF (started 18 months ago). HRCT shows bilateral ground-glass opacities and consolidation. BAL lymphocytosis. What is the most likely diagnosis and management?',
    ['PCP pneumonia — co-trimoxazole','Amiodarone pulmonary toxicity — stop amiodarone, consider prednisolone','IPF — pirfenidone','Sarcoidosis — observe','NSIP from connective tissue disease — immunosuppression'],
    1,
    'Amiodarone pulmonary toxicity (APT) occurs in 2–5% of patients on chronic therapy. HRCT shows bilateral GGO, consolidation, or NSIP-like pattern. BAL shows foamy macrophages and lymphocytosis. Diagnosis is clinical — there is no definitive test. Treatment: stop amiodarone (if possible — note that AF may recur), corticosteroids (prednisolone 40–60 mg) if severe. APT can be fatal. Monitor pulmonary function every 6 months in patients on long-term amiodarone.',
    'Amiodarone + bilateral GGO → amiodarone pulmonary toxicity → stop drug + steroids'),

  q('resp040','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 65-year-old man presents with progressive dyspnoea. Spirometry shows: FVC 52% (reduced), FEV₁ 55% (reduced), FEV₁/FVC 0.82 (normal). TLCO 48%. What does this pattern indicate?',
    ['Obstructive lung disease','Restrictive lung disease','Mixed obstructive-restrictive pattern','Upper airway obstruction','Normal spirometry'],
    1,
    'Restrictive lung disease: reduced FVC and FEV₁ with preserved (or elevated) FEV₁/FVC ratio. Causes include ILD (IPF, sarcoidosis, hypersensitivity pneumonitis), pleural disease, neuromuscular weakness, chest wall deformity (kyphoscoliosis). Reduced TLCO indicates parenchymal disease (ILD). If TLCO were normal with restriction, consider pleural or neuromuscular cause. TLC <80% on plethysmography confirms restriction.',
    'Reduced FVC + FEV₁, normal ratio = restrictive (TLC <80%)'),

  q('resp041','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 50-year-old woman with rheumatoid arthritis on methotrexate develops progressive dyspnoea and dry cough. HRCT shows bilateral subpleural GGO with fine reticulation, no honeycombing. BAL: 40% lymphocytes. What is the most likely ILD pattern and management?',
    ['UIP (IPF) — pirfenidone','NSIP — stop methotrexate, consider prednisolone','DIP — stop smoking','COP — high-dose prednisolone','LIP — azathioprine'],
    1,
    'RA-associated ILD: methotrexate causes drug-induced pneumonitis presenting with subacute dyspnoea, GGO on HRCT, and BAL lymphocytosis. NSIP is the most common ILD pattern in RA. Management: stop methotrexate as the first step (causative agent), then assess whether steroids are needed based on severity and functional impairment. If RA-ILD persists, immunosuppression with MMF or azathioprine may be needed. Monitor PFTs regularly.',
    'MTX-induced pneumonitis: stop methotrexate + consider prednisolone'),

  q('resp042','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 48-year-old man presents with severe COPD (FEV₁ 22%) and PaO₂ 6.8 kPa. He is stable on LTOT. He is referred for lung transplantation. What is the preferred transplant type for COPD?',
    ['Single lung transplantation (SLT)','Bilateral sequential lung transplantation (BSLT)','Heart-lung transplantation','Lobar living-donor transplantation','LVRS instead of transplantation'],
    1,
    'Bilateral sequential lung transplantation (BSLT/DALT) is preferred for COPD/emphysema as it provides better long-term outcomes and eliminates risk of native lung hyperinflation compressing the transplanted lung. SLT is an option for older patients with significant comorbidities. BSLT is also preferred for bronchiectasis and cystic fibrosis. SLT is preferred for pulmonary fibrosis (IPF) due to organ allocation and waitlist time.',
    'COPD transplant: bilateral sequential (BSLT) preferred'),

  q('resp043','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 30-year-old asthmatic woman is on step 3 treatment (low-dose ICS + LABA). Her asthma is uncontrolled (waking 2 nights per week, PEFR variability 25%). What should be the next treatment step?',
    ['Add montelukast (LTRA)','Increase ICS to medium dose','Add theophylline','Refer for severe asthma assessment','Switch LABA to a different one'],
    0,
    'NICE NG80 step 3 add-on: if uncontrolled on low-dose ICS + LABA, add a leukotriene receptor antagonist (LTRA, montelukast 10 mg). Medium-dose ICS is an alternative if LABA response is insufficient. Theophylline is step 4 add-on with narrow therapeutic window. Referral for severe asthma assessment (step 5) is for those uncontrolled despite steps 3–4. Biologics (omalizumab, mepolizumab) are step 5.',
    'Asthma step 3: add LTRA (montelukast) to ICS + LABA (NICE NG80)'),

  q('resp044','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 38-year-old woman with poorly controlled severe asthma has blood eosinophils of 450 cells/μL and FeNO of 68 ppb despite high-dose ICS + LABA + LTRA + maintenance prednisolone. What biologic therapy is most appropriate?',
    ['Omalizumab (anti-IgE)','Mepolizumab (anti-IL-5)','Benralizumab (anti-IL-5Rα)','Dupilumab (anti-IL-4/13)','Tezepelumab (anti-TSLP)'],
    1,
    'Mepolizumab and benralizumab are anti-IL-5 agents targeting eosinophilic inflammation. Both are NICE-approved for severe eosinophilic asthma with blood eosinophils ≥300 cells/μL. Mepolizumab reduces eosinophil counts by 80–90% and significantly reduces exacerbation rates (MENSA trial). Benralizumab depletes eosinophils nearly completely via ADCC (SIROCCO/CALIMA trials). Omalizumab is for allergic (IgE-mediated) asthma. Dupilumab is effective in type 2 inflammation regardless of eosinophils.',
    'Severe eosinophilic asthma (eos ≥300): mepolizumab or benralizumab'),

  q('resp045','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 55-year-old man has been treated for pulmonary TB with RHEZ for 8 weeks. Repeat sputum cultures remain positive. Drug sensitivity testing shows isoniazid and rifampicin resistance. What is this called and what is the recommended treatment?',
    ['Multidrug-resistant TB (MDR-TB) — bedaquiline-based regimen','Extensively drug-resistant TB (XDR-TB) — no effective treatment','Latent TB — treat with isoniazid prophylaxis','Drug-resistant TB — add ethambutol only','Inadequate treatment duration — continue RHEZ for longer'],
    0,
    'MDR-TB = resistance to at least rifampicin and isoniazid (the two most important first-line drugs). NICE CG117 / WHO guidelines: MDR-TB should be managed by specialist centres. Bedaquiline-containing regimens (BPaL: bedaquiline + pretomanid + linezolid, or BPaL-M including moxifloxacin) have transformed MDR-TB treatment. XDR-TB = MDR-TB plus resistance to fluoroquinolones and at least one injectable. Notify PHE, contact trace, and isolate.',
    'MDR-TB (R+H resistant): bedaquiline-based specialist regimen'),

  q('resp046','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 72-year-old man on long-term amiodarone is found to have bilateral pleural effusions. He is on furosemide and warfarin. What is the most likely cause of the effusions?',
    ['Malignant pleural disease','Amiodarone-induced pleuritis','Heart failure decompensation','Warfarin-induced haemothorax','Pulmonary embolism'],
    2,
    'Long-term amiodarone use and heart failure are both common in patients with AF. However, in this clinical context (elderly man on furosemide for heart failure), decompensated heart failure is the most likely cause of new bilateral pleural effusions. Amiodarone can rarely cause pleural disease, but it is less common. Bilateral effusions are typical of HF (transudates). Evaluation includes echocardiogram and Light\'s criteria on fluid if sampling needed.',
    'Bilateral effusions + amiodarone + furosemide: consider HF first'),

  q('resp047','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 68-year-old woman with COPD uses a salbutamol inhaler and tiotropium inhaler. She is admitted with an acute COPD exacerbation. ABG: pH 7.36, pCO₂ 5.8, pO₂ 7.9 on air. O₂ sats 89%. What oxygen should she receive?',
    ['High-flow O₂ at 15 L/min via non-rebreather mask','28% Venturi mask (2 L/min) targeting sats 88–92%','40% Venturi mask targeting sats ≥95%','No supplemental oxygen','NIV immediately'],
    1,
    'In COPD, target O₂ saturation is 88–92% to prevent hypercapnia worsening (hypoxic drive concern, though less common than thought). Controlled low-flow O₂ via Venturi mask (24–28%) is preferred. High-flow O₂ risks worsening hypercapnia and respiratory acidosis. The ABG here shows a near-normal pH with moderate hypoxaemia — suitable for controlled O₂. NIV is added if pH falls despite treatment.',
    'COPD exacerbation: target sats 88-92% via Venturi mask'),

  q('resp048','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 55-year-old woman with COPD presents with purulent sputum and worsening dyspnoea. She normally takes LAMA + LABA. She is febrile, RR 22, SpO₂ 92% on air. CURB-65 is 1. What treatment does she need?',
    ['Antibiotics only (amoxicillin)','Bronchodilators + prednisolone + antibiotics + controlled O₂','IV co-amoxiclav and admit','Add ICS and review as outpatient','NIV immediately'],
    1,
    'NICE NG115 COPD exacerbation management: increase bronchodilators (salbutamol ± ipratropium nebulisers), oral prednisolone 30 mg for 5 days (reduce recovery time and hospital stay — REDUCE trial showed 5 days non-inferior to 14), antibiotics for purulent sputum (amoxicillin, clarithromycin, or doxycycline), controlled O₂ to target sats 88–92%. Admit if CURB-65 ≥2 or social factors. CURB-65 1 may allow home treatment with close follow-up.',
    'COPD exacerbation: nebs + prednisolone 5 days + antibiotics + O₂'),

  q('resp049','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 45-year-old man presents with severe dyspnoea. CXR shows bilateral whiteout. He had a coronary artery bypass graft 5 days ago. Troponin is stable from post-op levels. Echo shows LVEF 55%, no new wall motion abnormality. PaO₂/FiO₂ = 110 mmHg. What is the diagnosis?',
    ['Cardiogenic pulmonary oedema','Acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS)','Pulmonary embolism','Hospital-acquired pneumonia','Haemothorax post-CABG'],
    1,
    'ARDS criteria (Berlin Definition): 1) Acute onset within 1 week; 2) Bilateral opacities on imaging; 3) Respiratory failure not explained by cardiac failure (LVEF normal here); 4) PaO₂/FiO₂ ≤300 (severe ≤100). Post-operative ARDS is a recognised complication. Management: lung-protective ventilation (tidal volume 6 mL/kg ideal body weight, PEEP optimisation), prone positioning for severe ARDS (PaO₂/FiO₂ <150), conservative fluid strategy.',
    'Bilateral whiteout + PF ratio ≤300 + normal heart = ARDS'),

  q('resp050','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 30-year-old man with known asthma is brought to A&E confused, cyanosed, and barely able to speak. PEFR <25% predicted. SpO₂ 84% on air. Arterial pCO₂ is 7.1 kPa. What is the immediate management?',
    ['IV aminophylline infusion','Immediate intubation and mechanical ventilation','IV magnesium 1.2–2 g + high-flow O₂ + nebulised salbutamol + HDU admission','Oral prednisolone 40 mg and nebulisers in outpatients','ICU review after spirometry'],
    2,
    'This is near-fatal asthma: PEFR <25%, hypoxia, hypercapnia (rising CO₂ in asthma indicates fatigue and impending respiratory arrest), and altered consciousness. Immediate actions: high-flow O₂ to maintain sats ≥94%, continuous nebulised salbutamol, IV hydrocortisone 100 mg, IV magnesium 1.2–2 g over 20 min (reduces intubation rate), HDU/ICU admission. Intubation is a last resort (high risk in asthma). Senior review and anaesthetics team on standby.',
    'Near-fatal asthma: O₂ + nebs + IV hydrocortisone + IV magnesium + HDU'),

  q('resp051','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 62-year-old man with IPF develops a sudden worsening of dyspnoea over 7 days. CXR shows new bilateral infiltrates superimposed on pre-existing reticular changes. No infection found on cultures. He has not been exposed to new drugs. What is this complication?',
    ['Aspiration pneumonia','IPF acute exacerbation','Pulmonary embolism','New opportunistic infection','Heart failure decompensation'],
    1,
    'Acute exacerbation of IPF (AE-IPF): rapid worsening of dyspnoea (within 30 days), new bilateral GGO/consolidation on HRCT superimposed on UIP background, no identifiable cause (infection, PE, heart failure excluded). In-hospital mortality exceeds 50%. Management: high-dose IV methylprednisolone (empirical), broad-spectrum antibiotics (exclude infection), supportive care. Poor prognosis. Consider palliative care and transplant eligibility.',
    'IPF + acute bilateral worsening (no infection) = AE-IPF → IV methylprednisolone'),

  q('resp052','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 50-year-old woman presents with episodic dyspnoea, stridor, and throat tightness. Spirometry shows a flattened inspiratory loop. Laryngoscopy during an episode shows paradoxical adduction of the vocal cords on inspiration. What is the diagnosis and treatment?',
    ['Anaphylaxis — adrenaline auto-injector','Vocal cord dysfunction (inducible laryngeal obstruction) — speech and language therapy','Asthma — increase ICS dose','Laryngeal cancer — ENT referral','Tracheomalacia — surgical repair'],
    1,
    'Vocal cord dysfunction (VCD) / inducible laryngeal obstruction (ILO): paradoxical adduction of the vocal cords on inspiration causes episodic inspiratory stridor and dyspnoea. Often misdiagnosed as asthma. Laryngoscopy during episode (gold standard) shows posterior glottic chink with anterior closure. Spirometry shows flattened inspiratory loop (extrathoracic obstruction). Treatment: speech and language therapy (breathing exercises, voice techniques), psychological support, treat triggers.',
    'Inspiratory stridor + flattened inspiratory loop = VCD → SLT'),

  q('resp053','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','basic',
    'A 45-year-old woman has bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy on CXR incidentally found. She has no symptoms. Her serum ACE is 82 U/L. EBUS-TBNA shows non-caseating granulomas with no organisms. What is the diagnosis and expected outcome?',
    ['Lymphoma — needs chemotherapy','Stage I sarcoidosis — 60–70% remit spontaneously','Active TB — start RHEZ','Primary malignancy — refer to oncology','Silicosis — occupational health referral'],
    1,
    'Stage I sarcoidosis (bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy alone, no pulmonary infiltrates) has an excellent prognosis with 60–80% spontaneous remission within 2 years. Non-caseating granulomas without caseation or organisms distinguish sarcoidosis from TB. Asymptomatic stage I requires no treatment — observation and monitoring. Treatment (corticosteroids) is reserved for symptomatic disease, pulmonary infiltrates, or extrapulmonary organ involvement (eyes, heart, CNS, kidneys, hypercalcaemia).',
    'Asymptomatic stage I sarcoidosis: observe (60-80% remit spontaneously)'),

  q('resp054','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','intermediate',
    'A 70-year-old man with severe IPF is being palliated. He has distressing breathlessness. What is the most evidence-based pharmacological intervention for refractory breathlessness in end-stage lung disease?',
    ['Diazepam 2 mg three times daily','Low-dose oral morphine (morphine sulphate 5 mg/4 hours)','High-dose prednisolone','Anxiolytic alone (lorazepam)','Nebulised furosemide'],
    1,
    'Low-dose opioids (oral morphine) are the most evidence-based treatment for refractory breathlessness in terminal respiratory disease, including IPF. Morphine reduces the sensation of dyspnoea without clinically significant respiratory depression at appropriate doses. NICE NG74 palliative care guidance supports opioids for breathlessness. Benzodiazepines are used for anxiety associated with breathlessness. Nebulised opioids and furosemide have insufficient evidence.',
    'End-stage breathlessness: low-dose oral morphine (evidence-based)'),

  q('resp055','respiratory','Respiratory Medicine','advanced',
    'A 60-year-old man with a 45-pack-year history is found to have right-sided vocal cord paralysis on laryngoscopy after presenting with a hoarse voice. CXR shows right hilar mass. What structure is most likely compressed, and why does right-sided RLN paralysis differ from left?',
    ['Right subclavian artery — right RLN loops around it; direct invasion more likely','Right RLN loops around the right subclavian artery; left RLN loops around the aortic arch so is longer and more often compressed by mediastinal/apical tumours','Both RLNs loop around the aortic arch symmetrically','The phrenic nerve is responsible for hoarseness','Left RLN is shorter and more vulnerable'],
    1,
    'The right recurrent laryngeal nerve loops around the right subclavian artery, staying more lateral and higher in the mediastinum. The left RLN loops under the aortic arch, making it much longer and more vulnerable to compression by mediastinal masses, lymphadenopathy, or aortic aneurysm. Therefore, a right-sided lung tumour can cause right RLN palsy by direct invasion/compression near the apex, whereas left-sided RLN palsy from a lung tumour suggests extensive mediastinal involvement or aortic arch disease.',
    'Right RLN: loops around right subclavian; Left RLN: loops under aortic arch (longer, more vulnerable)'),
];

